## Pull Request Rules

### Before Opening a PR
- [ ] All CI checks pass locally (`lint`, `typecheck`, `tests`)
- [ ] PR is **focused** — one feature or fix per PR; split large changes
- [ ] Branch is **rebased** on the latest `main` / `develop` (no merge commits in feature branches)
- [ ] Self-reviewed the diff — remove debug logs, commented-out code, and TODOs that aren't tracked
- [ ] Added or updated tests for the change
- [ ] Updated documentation if the public API or behaviour changed

### PR Title
- Follow the same Conventional Commits format as commit messages
- The title becomes the squash-merge commit message — make it meaningful

### PR Description Template
```markdown
## Summary
<!-- What does this PR do and why? -->

## Changes
<!-- Bullet list of key changes -->

## How to Test
<!-- Steps to verify the change works -->

## Screenshots / Recordings
<!-- For UI changes -->

## Related Issues
Closes #<issue-number>
```

### PR Size
- Aim for **< 400 lines changed** per PR — large PRs are rarely reviewed thoroughly
- If a PR must be large, add a guided walkthrough in the description
- Use **stacked PRs** for sequential changes that depend on each other

---

## Code Review

### For Authors
- Respond to every comment — either fix it, or explain why you disagree
- Mark resolved conversations as resolved only after addressing them
- Don't take review feedback personally — it's about the code, not you

### For Reviewers
- Review within **24 hours** of being assigned (working days)
- Distinguish between **blocking** (`must fix`) and **non-blocking** (`nit:`, `suggestion:`) comments
- Approve only when you would be comfortable owning the change
- Check: correctness, security, performance, test coverage, naming, and adherence to these conventions
- Use **conventional comment prefixes**: `nit:`, `question:`, `suggestion:`, `blocker:`

---

## Merging Strategy

- Use **Squash and Merge** for feature branches — keeps `main` history clean and linear
- Use **Merge Commit** for release branches and hotfixes — preserves the full history
- **Never force-push** to `main`, `develop`, or any shared branch
- Require at least **1 approval** before merging; 2 for changes to core/shared infrastructure
- Enable **branch protection** on `main`: require PR, require CI pass, no direct pushes
